    [x] How it is
        - Author: Samuel Beckett
        - tag: novel, poem, literature
        - year: 1961
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/789824
        - goodreads rating: 4.00
        - review
            - Probably I shouldn't have started Beckett by his admittedly most complex writing. But I couldn't really follow the lines. After 2-3 pages in I got a hang of it, could read, but then found myself spending too much energy reading things that should take tenth of hundredth of that much. I understand the point of art, but deliberately making something complicated with nothing really gained in the message or the emotions involved is not my type of art, or not even Tolstoy's! I always think of an artist as a person who gives a form or shape to something that an ordinary person can feel but is unable to reproduce. What Beckett is doing here might have that, I can't speak to that, but the hard work to make it inaccessible to those ordinary people is also definitely there and completely felt. So, if that was his goal, he's achieved it in my case.
