    [-] Enlightenment Now: The Case for Reason, Science, Humanism, and Progress
        - author: Steven Pinker
        - year: 2018
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35696171
        - goodreads rating: 4.19
        - review
            - starting this book I thought I'm gonna read a book that uses/praises science, logic, rigor for our current life, but I saw them misused in the early chapters and soon I realized I'm reading a religious book evangelizing super rich. I'm not sure what is with these Canadian psychologists, Jordan Peterson Gabor Mate, now Steven Pinker, who have no credibility in the topics they are talking about yet claim it because they have a degree in some unrelated area and can pretend they understand economics and want to start a new religion. I mean, an economist knows what's missing in their methodologies when making a claim, but I'm not sure if these people know, or they play ignorant so that they can dismiss criticism. Anyways, here's what I think after reading 11 chapters of this book. I skimmed the rest and it all repeats the same fallacies over and over but on different topics: Steven Pinker's "Enlightenment Now" commits the fundamental sin of scientific inquiry: it begins with its conclusion and works backward. This is not research—it is advocacy wrapped in graphs. The book's central dishonesty is methodological. Pinker asks causal and normative questions—Did Enlightenment values cause progress? Are current systems optimal? What should we do?—but attempts to answer them with descriptive statistics. He shows that certain metrics improved over time, then leaps to conclusions about causation, optimality, and future policy that his data simply cannot support. Time series analysis, even when done properly, cannot tell you why something happened or whether alternatives would have been better. It cannot provide counterfactuals. Yet Pinker presents line graphs as if they settle questions that require causal inference, philosophical argument, and rigorous comparison of alternative systems. He cherry-picks starting points not just to bias the analysis, but in ways that reveal the arbitrariness of the entire approach. Any competent analyst knows you cannot extract the conclusions he draws from the data he presents. Consider his treatment of absolute poverty reduction. Technological advancement—medicine, agriculture, energy—would have reduced absolute poverty under almost any political-economic system. China's massive poverty reduction under authoritarianism directly contradicts his thesis that liberal Enlightenment values caused these improvements. Yet he either ignores such inconvenient facts or hand-waves them away. He shows correlation and declares causation, repeatedly, without justification. His approach to metrics is strategic. He defines "progress" narrowly to include only measures that support his thesis while excluding wealth concentration, ecological sustainability, and the distribution of political power. He multiplies related metrics—infant mortality, child mortality, life expectancy at birth, life expectancy at age five—to create an illusion of independent evidence when he is simply measuring the same underlying phenomenon from different angles. This is not rigorous analysis; it is the appearance of rigor in service of predetermined conclusions. On inequality, Pinker goes beyond arguing that absolute poverty matters more than relative inequality. He actively dismisses concern about wealth concentration as "envy," positioning himself well to the right of even conservative economists who recognize inequality's effects on political power, economic efficiency, and social stability. His thesis is unfalsifiable: improvements prove him right, setbacks are temporary blips or prove we need more of his solutions, and critics are simply biased pessimists. The book's real function becomes clear when you ask who it serves. Bill Gates called it his "favorite book of all time." Tech billionaires and corporate conferences platform him enthusiastically. His work provides intellectual cover for resisting redistribution and defending concentrated corporate power—all while claiming scientific neutrality. His nominal social liberalism on issues like gay rights functions primarily as permission structure for hard-right economic positions. Most damaging is what Pinker does to the concept of Enlightenment itself. He has colonized terms like "reason," "science," and "progress" for his specific political project, making it harder for anyone committed to genuine empiricism to use these terms without appearing to endorse his ideology. He presents a false choice: accept his defense of current systems or be labeled anti-Enlightenment. This poisons the well for honest inquiry. The actual Enlightenment tradition included radical egalitarians, critics of concentrated power, and thinkers who understood that reason meant questioning everything—including the systems that benefit the powerful. Voltaire challenged authority. Rousseau critiqued inequality. The Encyclopédistes documented knowledge while examining power structures. They would be appalled by someone using "Enlightenment" to defend plutocracy and dismiss urgent problems. We desperately need rigorous, evidence-based thinking about climate change, inequality, democratic erosion, and technological risk. Instead, Pinker offers motivated reasoning masquerading as science, certainty where there should be questions, and complacency where there should be urgency. He has made the path for those who want genuine enlightenment harder to navigate by creating a neo-religion that treats existing systems as vindicated, billionaires as heroes, and critics as heretics. "Enlightenment Now" is not a contribution to human understanding. It is an obstacle to it—a sophisticated exercise in using the language and authority of science to defend power and discourage the hard work of building something better.
