    [x] A Swim in a Pond in the Rain
        - author: George Saunders
        - year: 2021
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53487237
        - goodreads rating: 4.53
        - review
            - There is an added bonus in this book, the book sets to teach you how to read/write/ and think, but since it includes the short stories, you'll enjoy reading some masterpieces too! A few friends had read and enjoyed this book, so I thought I'd give it a try. I'm interested in storytelling and I think it's important to have the skills to convey a certain message in a way that the reader wants to continue reading, not necessarily agreeing. These are fundamental skills that I lack and I wish to have. The book was fascinating. It even talks about how to get the reader to disagree with you! What hit me the most wasn't like any "aha" moment - it was more like: duh, of course that works this way, now how can I do this more programmatically? Each story had its unique set of techniques. It was amazing that Saunders didn't repeat them over and over, instead contrasted them against each other or used one to complete another. Using flawed characters is one level, but using a flawed author's voice by Gogol was a whole other level. Initially when I read that story I was like, so what? What is this trying to say? What is so good about this? But when he breaks it down, I start learning how to read more than how to write. It shows how some authors work on your thoughts without you even noticing they are doing that. In the first chapter Saunders breaks down each story page by page. At the end of each page he asks questions, and the questions evolve as you go. Early on he asks: - Look away from the page and summarize what you know so far - What are you curious about? - Where do you think the story is headed? But then he adds more complex ones: - Is this a story yet? Why yes/no? - What if we ended right here - would that be satisfying? - What is this story "about" for you? - How were you made to care about this character? He teaches you how to respond to these questions too - concepts like increased specification, meaningful action, expectation-setting. He forces you to consider alternatives: why this person, why not someone else, why this day, why the weather is nice? All these questions give you reasons to appreciate the story as a reader. I think he expect the reader to the same as they go through the rest of the chapters, I didn't really do it, but I think I should :p I'm thinking of two things he mentions. One is that every piece in a short story has a goal, it needs to be efficient. When something enters the text it needs to change the outcome somehow. The other is always escalating. That's what keeps readers reading. From chapter to chapter, I feel like I could use some of the previous techniques, though it requires slowing down by orders of magnitude, which I don't always like to do. But when done, it leaves such a deeper impact on me. I feel like I'm not gonna use them on everything I read, because some writers might not even be worth that much time, but I'm certainly going to do it with the ones that I think there's something to be learned from. I want to make this into a process when I'm reading. I can do all these things, and when I've done it enough, it will become second nature to me. I'll do it as I'm reading, I don't need to pause every page and do it - I'll do it as I read every word in my head. This is only from the first chapter though. In the next chapters he gets deeper and deeper, and more complex questions need to be answered. I think I have to go through the book one more time and extract these learnings and methodologies as I read it. -- I listened to the audiobook which was amazing since the author reads it, but there are other people who read the short stories, it was a great experience. But now I'm going to go through the ebook again and highlight parts and make notes.
