    [x] The Idiot
        - author: Fyodor Dostoevsky
        - year: 1869
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12505
        - goodreads rating: 4.21
        - review
            - It is hard to believe that this was written in 1860's, such contemporary metters are discussed at length here. It is clear that this was written after Dostoyevsky's exile, but I had to check to make sure it was written after crime and punishment, but only 3 years after. This one is a lot more coherent and has more upfront about what it wants to say. The whole structure of the book is set inside a romantic drama, almost a soap opera even, but it seems like the author has no desire in it while he knows very well how to use it to hook the audience. There's often a very heated romance scene, and suddenly something happens and a character goes on a very long monolog about a societal or philosophical topic. It's not even clear that if Dostoyevsky agrees with the points of those characters, he's likely just examining those ideas by putting them into words in this way. The various parts of the book have very different paces, for example, the entire part one happens in just one day, morning to evening. Some parts over several months. The last part is narrated as a report as concise as possible. Overall, it is a very engaging book and explores important themes. While it is said that the book focuses on religion and nationalism, I didn't find it a main point of the book. The interactions of the characters were the most fascinating part.
