    [x] An Immense World: How Animal Senses Reveal the Hidden Realms Around Us
        - author: Ed Yong
        - year: 2022
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/59575939
        - goodreads rating: 4.46
        - review
            - I got this book as a gift for a friend who is very interested in understanding what animals think and feel. We were just talking about how a hummingbird would see humans a slow animal like we see slugs. Then a colleague talked about this book and later Mike read and liked it. So I got the book and couldn't resist it. One of the positive points of the book is the use of scientific research and explaining the results in a way that I can understand, and in a very engaging way. I think that's a great gift that Ed has and uses it beautifully to create awareness and to share knowledge. Of course the book has some biases, and is aware of it and doesn't hide it. But that's besides the point of this book. That birds can smell or not is an important question, but the answer is not as important as asking and trying to answer that question. The other thing I liked about the book is the refrain from ranking and comparing species. Though it inevitably does it, but it tries not to. The number of research articles that it summarizes, the stories that it recites from researchers working on these topics, the road that the science has taken to answer such questions, and the structure of the book, they are all such great wealth of knowledge that definitely has taken years to collect and organize. I'm so happy I read this book and so glad that there are people who write such books. There was no way for me to get so much information and expand my point of view in such a short time. This is a highly recommended book to anyone who has wondered about animals (and humans for that matter) in any capacity.
    [-] How Humans Judge Machines
