    [x] Atlas of the Heart: Mapping Meaningful Connection and the Language of Human Experience
        - author: Brené Brown
        - year: 2021
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58330567
        - goodreads rating: 4.32
        - review
            - This is an amazing book, the author is trustworthy, and the content are extremely useful. Knowing about the definition of the words that are about emotions did not directly give me a way to communicate them better, or get help, but as a mathematician, I highly respect the fact that someone has put in an effort to define those carefully. On top of that some of these words are clustered together and compared with each other. I think this is a very fundamental piece of work for later efforts related to emotions. However, I think there could be more done on terms of clustering, but it might require years of research which is not done yet. One of the weaker aspects of the book is some of the emotions are defined only in comparison to other emotions, like "x is not y" type of definition, which I don't find helpful on their own. Another part that could be improved is some times the author tries to convince the reader that the word x doesn't mean what most people think it means and that it means something else. While from a historical point of view they might be accurate, the role of the language, and partly the goal of this book, is to enable people to connect concepts and words so that can be communicated. I appreciate an effort to unify the definition of a concept, though it should be done the other way around I think. Oh, and the audio book version with the voice of the author is amazing. They read it so perfectly. I love the parts they repeat a sentence, or add exclamations. There are two things that encourages me to read more from this author: that I think they have a lot more to say when it comes to treating a person, and that concept of "near enemies". The part about treating is apparent from all the "advice"-like paragraphs in the later chapters. Someone who goes on and writes an entire book to just start talking with someone about their emotions should be amazing at their job, even if our points of view don't match, I'd love to learn from them. And the concept of near enemies is just fascinating. I think it'd apply to so many other things too, I'd like to learn more about what people have categorized in this way.
