    [x] The Complete Persepolis
        - author: Marjane Satrapi
        - year: 2007
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/991197
        - goodreads rating: 4.40
        - review
            - I learned about the book from the animation based on this book, and while I found it a nice movie to watch, the details were a bit cheesy and holywood-like. So, I always recommend the film to friends with a few words of caution first. I stumbled upon the book on my friend's bookshelf and they let me borrow it, and starting from the first few pages I got hooked. Unlike the film, the book is a personal account of what happened to Marjane during those years, it feels honest, to the point, and with the right amount of details that makes you develop a sense of the situation at the time, it doesn't try to convince you that everyone had the same experience, but quite opposite, it shows that different people were experiencing very different things, and tries to be as open as a teenage girl in that situation can be, reflecting on others' emotions and situations. In the wake of what's happening these days in Iran, it was a good point of reference for me to have since as a boy, I haven't come to fully appreciate what girls go through in my country, and this helped a bit, maybe it could serve as a starting point to enquire more. All in all, it is an excellent book, engaging, and hard to put down.
    [x] The Reason I Jump: the Inner Voice of a Thirteen-Year-Old Boy with Autism
        - author: Naoki Higashida
        - year: 2005
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16113737
        - goodreads rating: 3.88
        - review
            - I leaned about the book after watching a movie with the same name. The movie follows a few children around the world that have autism and are speechless. The book is by a 13 year old (at the time) Japanese boy, Naoki, who is autistic and is speechless. The most fascinating thing about the book for me is the level of understanding of the author not only of the people with autism but also of non-autistic ones and the ability to set them side by side and describe their differences. The ability to learn a language of people with concepts foreign to him, and then try to figure out how would they think about his situation and explain it to them in their language. It's something that definitely non-autistic people have failed at it, and have completely given up even trying. The next big thing about the book for me is how clearly it describes all of "my" frustrations with people around me. There were numerous times that he says only if people would understand this or that about me, and I had never felt like someone describing my feelings so well. I feel I'm probably half way between autistic and non-autistic people. Finally, these are the words of a representative of a group of people that we don't understand much if at all, and nothing is more exciting to get to know them from their point of view. The only thing I wish was different about the book is that it didn't spend the entire book answering questions that others have or might have about autism, rather talking a bit more about what he wanted us to know. Still does it to a certain extent. And yes, I totally recommended the movie too.
    [x] I Have More Souls Than One
