    [] Why nations fail
        - author: Daron Acemoğlu
        - year: 2012
        - goodreads: https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12158480
        - goodreads rating: 4.09
        - review
            - Rants so far: I'm starting to lose interest in the book. It starts with the premise that putting decision-making power in people's hands is what makes nations economically grow and that what makes nations flourish. Quite the opposite of the topic of the title of the book. It wants the reader to implicitly conclude not putting power in people's hands would make nations fail. Or maybe they didn't really want to write about why nations fail, but this title came afterwards and sounds way more sexy than whatever else they had in mind and they kept it. Aside from nitpicking on the title, the first 6 chapters of the book are repetitively talking about how important democracy is and as a result how bad anything else is. They go on and on by viewing every single event in the world and history through this lens and to justify their already assumed premise. I would have liked to see a bit more rigorous discussion and arguments here, rather than repeating it a million times. Of course if you have a point of view you can go and view everything through that lens and be happy that your view "doesn't fall apart", but that also doesn't prove anything. While I have my opinions about democracy, I agree that putting power in people's hand is the best course of action, but I needed something more, something that makes a logical connection, not just anecdotes, for those who already believe in it. I at least expected way more than a UChicago economics professor and an economics Nobel prize winner. I'm going to try to read a bit more, but if it continues this way, I'm going to stop reading it. They also don't ever mention the places where their premise fails. Any reasonable person knows they cannot have a theory that explains EVERYTHING. Well, except maybe for economists? And some phyisicists at a certain point in the last century. This approach isn't very scientific. If you are writing a several hundred pages book at least include what isn't working in your theory. I really enjoy the historical context they provide though. I belive it is very hard to get such a collection anywhere else so easily. Though I keep in mind that the way they have written the book, now I susptect they have hand picked the "parts" of the story that adhere to their view. Some of their "writing techniques" are also anooying. I don't need to know the long unpronounceable names of random people in a random tribe in ancient Maya to get the story, you're just trying to force me to believe you by creating authority.
